Part One: Data Exploration

The dataset we will study for this assignment contains information about health insurance costs for individuals with no dependents (children) in the United States. The information contained in the data is:

  • Age of primary beneficiary

  • Gender of primary beneficiary (only female, male recorded)

  • Body mass index, providing an understanding of body, weights that are relatively high or low relative to height, objective index of body weight (kg / m ^ 2) using the ratio of height to weight, ideally 18.5 to 24.9

  • Whether the beneficiary smokes

  • The beneficiarys residential area in the US, northeast, southeast, southwest, northwest.

  • Individual medical costs billed by health insurance

  1. Read in the dataset, and display some summaries of the data.

  1. Make up to three plots comparing the response variable (charges) to one of the predictor variables. Briefly discuss each plot.
Code 
(ggplot(insurance, aes(x = "bmi", y = "charges", color = "sex"))
+ geom_point()
+ facet_wrap("~ smoker")
+ labs(x = "BMI", y = "Medical Charges", color = "Sex",
       title = "BMI and Medical Charges by Gender and Smoking")
+ theme_bw()
)

The plot above demonstrates the relationship between BMI and medical charges, separated by smoking status, with points colored by gender. Charges generally increase with BMI, especially for smokers, suggesting that both BMI and smoking significantly impact healthcare costs. There also doesnt appear to be a drastic difference between males and females.

Code 
(ggplot(insurance, aes(x = "age", y = "charges", color = "sex"))
+ geom_point()
+ facet_wrap("~ smoker")
+ labs(x = "Age", y = "Medical Charges", color = "Sex",
       title = "Age and Medical Charges by Gender and Smoking")
+ theme_bw()
)

This plot above displays the relationship between age and medical charges, separated by smoking status, with points colored by gender. Medical charges tend to rise with age, particularly among smokers, indicating that older smokers may incur significantly higher healthcare costs. The color differentiation demonstrates that gender affects medical charges consistently.

Code 
(ggplot(insurance, aes(x = "region", y = "charges", fill = "sex"))
+ geom_bar(stat = "identity")
+ facet_wrap("~ smoker")
+ labs(x = "Region", y = "Medical Charges", fill = "Sex",
       title = "Region and Medical Charges by Gender and Smoking")
+ theme_bw()
+ theme(axis_text_x=element_text(rotation=45, hjust=1))
)

This plot above shows how medical charges vary across regions, separated by gender and smoking status. Among smokers, the southeast region tends to have significantly higher medical chargers than other regions. While among non-smokers, the northeast regions has slightly higher medical charges than other regions. We also see that there are larger disparities between medical charges for male and females among smokers than non-smokers.

Part Two: Simple Linear Models

  1. Construct a simple linear model to predict the insurance charges from the beneficiarys age. Discuss the model fit, and interpret the coefficient estimates.
Code 
# model 1
X = insurance[["age"]]
y = insurance["charges"]

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=1)

lr = LinearRegression()

lr_pipeline = Pipeline(
  [
  ("linear_regression", LinearRegression())]
)

lr_fitted = lr_pipeline.fit(X_train, y_train)


y_pred_test = lr_fitted.predict(X_test)
y_pred_train = lr_fitted.predict(X_train)

mse_train = mean_squared_error(y_train, y_pred_train)
rsquared_train = r2_score(y_train, y_pred_train)

mse_test = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_test)
rsquared_test = r2_score(y_test, y_pred_test)

print("Model 1:")
print("Intercept: ", lr_fitted.named_steps['linear_regression'].intercept_.__round__(2))
print("Coefficient: ", lr_fitted.named_steps['linear_regression'].coef_[0].__round__(2))
print("Train MSE:", mse_train.__round__(2))
print("Train R^2: ", rsquared_train.__round__(2))
print("Test MSE:", mse_test.__round__(2))
print("Test R^2: ", rsquared_test.__round__(2))

The model is: Predicted Charges = 3769.22 + 231.67(Age)

Based on the r-squared of 0.12, 12% of the variation in medical charges is explained by the line of regression, indicating a poor fit of the model. The MSE at 87360446.32 indicates an RMSE of 9346.68, indicating that the model is missing the true insurance costs by approximately $9346.68, which isnt great.

Every time age increases by one year, predicted medical charges increase by approximately $231.67 on average. When Age is at 0 years, predicted medical charges are at approximately $3769.22, however we wouldnt expect to see medical charges for an age of 0.

X = insurance[["age", "sex"]]

  [
    ("dummify", 
    OneHotEncoder(sparse_output = False, handle_unknown='ignore', drop = "first"),
    make_column_selector(dtype_include=object))
  ],
  remainder = "passthrough"
).set_output(transform="pandas")

lr_pipeline1 = Pipeline(
  [("preprocessing", ct),
  ("linear_regression", LinearRegression())]
)

lr_fitted1 = lr_pipeline1.fit(X_train, y_train)

y_pred_test1 = lr_pipeline1.predict(X_test)
y_pred_train1 = lr_pipeline1.predict(X_train)

mse_train1 = mean_squared_error(y_train, y_pred_train1)
rsquared_train1 = r2_score(y_train, y_pred_train1)

mse_test1 = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_test1)
rsquared_test1 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred_test1)

print("Model 2 (Age and Sex)")

Based on the models in Q2 and Q3, Model 3 fits the data better as it has a lower MSE and higher r-squared.   1. Perhaps the relationships are not linear. Fit a model that uses age and age^2 as predictors. How do the MSE and R-squared compare to the model in P2 Q1?
Code 
X = insurance[["age"]]
y = insurance["charges"]

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.2, random_state=1)

ct = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[
        ("poly", PolynomialFeatures(degree = 2, include_bias=False), ["age"])
    ],
    remainder="drop"
).set_output(transform="pandas")

lr_pipeline4 = Pipeline(
  [("preprocessing", ct),
  ("linear_regression", LinearRegression())]
)

lr_fitted4 = lr_pipeline4.fit(X_train, y_train)

y_pred_test4 = lr_pipeline4.predict(X_test)
y_pred_train4 = lr_pipeline4.predict(X_train)

mse_train4 = mean_squared_error(y_train, y_pred_train4)
rsquared_train4 = r2_score(y_train, y_pred_train4)

mse_test4 = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_test4)
rsquared_test4 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred_test4)

print("Model 5 (Age and Age^2 Model)")
print("Coefficient for Age: ", lr_fitted4.named_steps['linear_regression'].coef_[0].__round__(2))
print("Coefficient for Age^2: ", lr_fitted4.named_steps['linear_regression'].coef_[1].__round__(2))
print("Intercept: ", lr_fitted4.named_steps['linear_regression'].intercept_.__round__(2))
print("Train MSE:", mse_train4.__round__(2))
print("Train R^2: ", rsquared_train4.__round__(2))
print("Test MSE:", mse_test4.__round__(2))
print("Test R^2: ", rsquared_test4.__round__(2))

With the addition of the age^2 variable, the r-squared value appears to decrease from 0.15 to 0.12 between Q1 and Q2 while the MSE tends to increase from 83569014.93 (Q1) to 87413315.31 (Q2). This indicates that the model in Part 3 Q1 performs better due to the higher r-squared and smaller MSE. Overall, the changes suggest that adding the squared term does not enhance the models predictive capability.

With the addition of these polynomials, there is a significant decrease in the r-squared and increase in the MSE. This indicates that the model in Part 3 Q1 performs better due to the higher r-squared and smaller MSE. Overall, the changes suggest that adding the squared term does not enhance the models predictive capability.

Using any variables in this dataset, and any polynomial of those variables, find the model that best predicts on the new data after being fit on the original data.

Make a plot showing the residuals of your final chosen model.

Code 
# create training data from original dataset
X_train = encoded_df.drop(columns=['charges'])
y_train = encoded_df[["charges"]]

# create dummy variables for new dataset
encoded_df_new = pd.get_dummies(insurance_new).astype(int)

# create test data from new dataset
X_test = encoded_df_new.drop(columns=['charges'])
y_test = encoded_df_new[["charges"]]

variables = ["age", "bmi", "sex", "smoker", "region"]
y_variable = "charges"

#function for preprocessing pipeline
def create_preprocessing_pipeline(variables, poly_degree = None):
    transformers = []
    
    #allow age to be a polynomial (quantitative var)
    if "age" in variables:
        if poly_degree is not None:
            transformers.append(("poly_age", PolynomialFeatures(degree = poly_degree), ["age"]))
        else:
            transformers.append(("age", StandardScaler(), ["age"]))
    
    #allow age to be a polynomial (quantitative var)
    if "bmi" in variables:
        if poly_degree is not None:
            transformers.append(("poly_bmi", PolynomialFeatures(degree = poly_degree), ["bmi"]))
        else:
            transformers.append(("bmi", StandardScaler(), ["bmi"]))
    
    #categorical variables dummified
    if "sex" in variables:
        transformers.append(("sex", OneHotEncoder(drop = "first", sparse_output = False), ["sex"]))
    if "smoker" in variables:
        transformers.append(("smoker", OneHotEncoder(drop = "first", sparse_output = False), ["smoker"]))
    if "region" in variables:
        transformers.append(("region", OneHotEncoder(drop = "first", sparse_output = False), ["region"]))

    return ColumnTransformer(transformers, remainder = "drop")

#initialize for results
results = []

#iterate over all combinations of variables
for r in range(1, len(variables) + 1):
    for combo in combinations(variables, r):
        #loop through polynomial degrees (1-4 seems reasonable to avoid overfitting)
        for degree in range(1, 4):
            #preprocessing pipeline using function
            ct_poly = create_preprocessing_pipeline(combo, poly_degree=degree)
            pipeline = Pipeline([
                ("preprocessing", ct_poly),
                ("linear_regression", LinearRegression())
            ])
            
            #create the parameter grid
            param_grid = {}
            if "age" in combo:
                param_grid["preprocessing__poly_age__degree"] = [degree]
            if "bmi" in combo:
                param_grid["preprocessing__poly_bmi__degree"] = [degree]
            
            #use grid search
            grid_search = GridSearchCV(pipeline, param_grid, cv=5, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error')
            pipeline.fit(insurance[list(combo)], insurance[y_variable])

            # make predictions
            predictions = pipeline.predict(insurance_new[list(combo)])

            #get mse
            mse = mean_squared_error(insurance_new[y_variable], predictions)

            #store results
            results.append({
                "variables": combo,
                "degree": degree,
                "mse": mse
            })

#convert to dataframe
results_df = pd.DataFrame(results)

#display
print(results_df.sort_values(by="mse"))

The code above selects the model with the lowest MSE to minimize the prediction error for the target variable charges, and the best results suggest that adding a polynomial degree for age and bmi improves performance compared to using just linear terms. Based on the residual plot, there doesnt appear to be homoskedasticity and there also appears to be two lines to the right of the plot. These indicate that there are some areas where the model consistently overestimates or underestimates the actual values. This likely indicates that the model could benefit from an interaction variable to capture some of the underlying features. For example, conceptually speaking, it would be likely to see a relationship between bmi and age, since we would expect bmi to increase with age, indicating the need for an interaction variable to enhance the models accuracy.
